author: Henrietta_Fore;
title: How we can help young people build a better future

aws-transcripts.transcript: Today there are one point 8,000,000,000 young people between the ages of 10 and 24 in the world. It is the largest cohort in human history. Meeting their needs will be a big challenge, but it's also a big opportunity. They hold our shared future in their hands. Every day we've read about young people lending their ideas and passions to fighting for change, social change, political change, change in their communities. Imagine what they'll create breakthroughs, inventions, maybe new medicines, new modes of transportation, new ways to communicate sustainable economies and maybe even a world at peace. But this opportunity, this youth dividend is not a given. One point 8,000,000,000 young women and young men are standing at the door of adult to it. Are they ready? Right now, Too few of them are my favorite. Part of my job at UNICEF is a chance to talk, to meet with and hear from young people all around the world. And they tell me about their hopes and dreams on. They have amazing hopes and dreams for what they'll accomplish in their lives. But what they're also telling me is that they have fears. They feel they're facing a series of urgent crises, a crisis of demographics, a crisis of education, Ah, crisis of employment, a crisis of violence and a crisis for girls. If you look at these crises, you realize that they're urgent and they need to be addressed now because they tell us that they're worried. They're worried that they might not get the education that they need. And you know what? They're right. 200,000,000 adolescents are out of school worldwide, about the population of Brazil, and those that are in school feel that they may not be getting the right skills globally. Six in 10 children and young people do not meet the minimum proficiency level for reading and mathematics. No country can be successful if nearly half of its population of young people are unable to read or write. And what about the lucky few who are in secondary school? Many of them are dropping out because they're worried that they're not getting skills that they can use to make a livelihood, and sometimes their parents can no longer afford the fees. It's a tragedy, and young people are also telling me that they're worried about employment, that they won't be able to find a job and again there, right? Every month, 10,000,000 young people reach working age. It's a staggering number. Some will go on for further education, but many will enter. The workforce on our world is not creating 10,000,000 new jobs each month. The competition is fierce for the jobs that are available.
